0:11:29.292,000 --> 0:11:31,000
for Egyptians to use,

265
0:11:31.766,000 --> 0:11:33,000
serving slow but sweet Internet connection

266
0:11:34.603,000 --> 0:11:35,000
for Egyptians.

267
0:11:36.004,000 --> 0:11:37,000
This worked.

268
0:11:37.299,000 --> 0:11:38,000
It worked so well, in fact,

269
0:11:39.092,000 --> 0:11:41,000
one guy even used it to download an episode

270
0:11:41.372,000 --> 0:11:45,000
of "How I Met Your Mother."

271
0:11:45.71,000 --> 0:11:48,000
But while Egypt's future is still uncertain,

272
0:11:49.631,000 --> 0:11:51,000
when the same thing happened in Syria

273
0:11:52.284,000 --> 0:11:53,000
just one year later,

274
0:11:53.804,000 --> 0:11:56,000
Telecomix were prepared with those Internet lines,

275
0:11:57.539,000 --> 0:11:58,000
and Anonymous,

276
0:11:58.708,000 --> 0:12:,000
they were perhaps the first international group

277
0:12:00.954,000 --> 0:12:01,000
to officially denounce the actions

278
0:12:02.658,000 --> 0:12:03,000
of the Syrian military

279
0:12:04.571,000 --> 0:12:06,000
by defacing their website.

280
0:12:07.375,000 --> 0:12:1,000
But with this sort of power,

281
0:12:10.867,000 --> 0:12:12,000
it really depends on where you stand,

282
0:12:13.213,000 --> 0:12:16,000
because one man's hero

283
0:12:16.722,000 --> 0:12:18,000
can be another's villain,

284
0:12:18.969,000 --> 0:12:2,000
and so the Syrian Electronic Army

285
0:12:21.367,000 --> 0:12:23,000
is a pro-Assad group of hackers

286
0:12:23.838,000 --> 0:12:25,000
who support his contentious regime.

287
0:12:26.503,000 --> 0:12:28,000
They've taken down multiple high-profile targets

288
0:12:29.185,000 --> 0:12:3,000
in the past few years,

289
0:12:30.82,000 --> 0:12:33,000
including the Associated Press's Twitter account,

290
0:12:34.203,000 --> 0:12:37,000
in which they posted a message

291
0:12:37.219,000 --> 0:12:39,000
about an attack on the White House

292
0:12:39.375,000 --> 0:12:42,000
injuring President Obama.

293
0:12:42.638,000 --> 0:12:44,000
This tweet was fake, of course,

294
0:12:44.783,000 --> 0:12:46,000
but the resulting drop in the Dow Jones index

295
0:12:47.722,000 --> 0:12:5,000
that day was most certainly not,

296
0:12:51.099,000 --> 0:12:54,000
and a lot of people lost a lot of money.

297
0:12:54.361,000 --> 0:12:57,000
This sort of thing is happening all over the world right now.

298
0:12:58.267,000 --> 0:13:,000
In conflicts from the Crimean Peninsula

299
0:13:01.214,000 --> 0:13:03,000
to Latin America,

300
0:13:03.576,000 --> 0:13:05,000
from Europe to the United States,

301
0:13:05.88,000 --> 0:13:08,000
hackers are a force for social,

302
0:13:08.937,000 --> 0:13:11,000
political and military influence.

303
0:13:12.703,000 --> 0:13:14,000
As individuals or in groups,

304
0:13:14.954,000 --> 0:13:16,000
volunteers or military conflicts,

305
0:13:17.594,000 --> 0:13:19,000
there are hackers everywhere.

306
0:13:20.235,000 --> 0:13:22,000
They come from all walks of life,

307
0:13:22.33,000 --> 0:13:26,000
ethnicities, ideologies and genders, I might add.

308
0:13:27.254,000 --> 0:13:3,000
They are now shaping the world's stage.

309
0:13:31.053,000 --> 0:13:33,000
Hackers represent an exceptional force for change

310
0:13:33.898,000 --> 0:13:35,000
in the 21st century.

311
0:13:36.062,000 --> 0:13:38,000
This is because access to information

312
0:13:38.599,000 --> 0:13:41,000
is a critical currency of power,

313
0:13:41.912,000 --> 0:13:43,000
one which governments would like to control,

314
0:13:44.878,000 --> 0:13:46,000
a thing they attempt to do by setting up

315
0:13:47.339,000 --> 0:13:5,000
all-you-can-eat surveillance programs,

316
0:13:50.999,000 --> 0:13:52,000
a thing they need hackers for, by the way.

317
0:13:53.737,000 --> 0:13:55,000
And so the establishment has long had

318
0:13:56.384,000 --> 0:13:59,000
a love-hate relationship when it comes to hackers,

319
0:14:00.091,000 --> 0:14:02,000
because the same people who demonize hacking

320
0:14:02.849,000 --> 0:14:07,000
also utilize it at large.

321
0:14:07.931,000 --> 0:14:08,000
Two years ago,

322
0:14:09.179,000 --> 0:14:11,000
I saw General Keith Alexander.

323
0:14:11.952,000 --> 0:14:15,000
He's the NSA director and U.S. cyber commander,

324
0:14:16.17,000 --> 0:14:19,000
but instead of his four star general uniform,

325
0:14:19.878,000 --> 0:14:21,000
he was wearing jeans and a t-shirt.

326
0:14:22.174,000 --> 0:14:23,000
This was at DEF CON,

327
0:14:23.918,000 --> 0:14:26,000
the world's largest hacker conference.

328
0:14:27.023,000 --> 0:14:28,000
Perhaps like me, General Alexander

329
0:14:28.95,000 --> 0:14:31,000
didn't see 12,000 criminals that day in Vegas.

330
0:14:32.77,000 --> 0:14:35,000
I think he saw untapped potential.

331
0:14:35.881,000 --> 0:14:38,000
In fact, he was there to give a hiring pitch.

332
0:14:39.254,000 --> 0:14:41,000
"In this room right here," he said,

333
0:14:41.894,000 --> 0:14:43,000
"is the talent our nation needs."

334
0:14:44.284,000 --> 0:14:47,000
Well, hackers in the back row replied,

335
0:14:47.664,000 --> 0:14:49,000
"Then stop arresting us."

336
0:14:49.79,000 --> 0:14:52,000
(Applause)

337
0:14:53.224,000 --> 0:14:55,000
Indeed, for years,

338
0:14:55.803,000 --> 0:14:57,000
hackers have been on the wrong side of the fence,

339
0:14:58.619,000 --> 0:15:,000
but in light of what we know now,

340
0:15:01.527,000 --> 0:15:05,000
who is more watchful of our online world?

341
0:15:05.8,000 --> 0:15:08,000
The rules of the game are not that clear anymore,

342
0:15:08.806,000 --> 0:15:11,000
but hackers are perhaps the only ones

343
0:15:12.218,000 --> 0:15:15,000
still capable of challenging overreaching governments

344
0:15:16.101,000 --> 0:15:18,000
and data-hoarding corporates

345
0:15:18.316,000 --> 0:15:2,000
on their own playing field.

346
0:15:20.794,000 --> 0:15:23,000
To me, that represents hope.

347
0:15:23.914,000 --> 0:15:24,000
For the past three decades,

348
0:15:25.238,000 --> 0:15:26,000
hackers have done a lot of things,

349
0:15:26.789,000 --> 0:15:29,000
but they have also impacted civil liberties,

350
0:15:30.006,000 --> 0:15:32,000
innovation and Internet freedom,

351
0:15:32.376,000 --> 0:15:34,000
so I think it's time we take a good look

352
0:15:35.305,000 --> 0:15:37,000
at how we choose to portray them,

353
0:15:37.435,000 --> 0:15:4,000
because if we keep expecting them to be the bad guys,

354
0:15:41.019,000 --> 0:15:44,000
how can they be the heroes too?

355
0:15:44.489,000 --> 0:15:46,000
My years in the hacker world

356
0:15:46.5,000 --> 0:15:47,000
have made me realize

357
0:15:48.142,000 --> 0:15:53,000
both the problem and the beauty about hackers:

358
0:15:53.875,000 --> 0:15:56,000
They just can't see something broken in the world

359
0:15:57.033,000 --> 0:15:58,000
and leave it be.

360
0:15:58.68,000 --> 0:15:59,000
They are compelled

361
0:16:00.36,000 --> 0:16:03,000
to either exploit it or try and change it,

362
0:16:03.89,000 --> 0:16:06,000
and so they find the vulnerable aspects

363
0:16:07.806,000 --> 0:16:09,000
in our rapidly changing world.

364
0:16:09.94,000 --> 0:16:13,000
They make us, they force us to fix things

365
0:16:14.282,000 --> 0:16:15,000
or demand something better,

366
0:16:16.001,000 --> 0:16:17,000
and I think we need them

367
0:16:17.995,000 --> 0:16:19,000
to do just that,

368
0:16:20.201,000 --> 0:16:23,000
because after all, it is not information

369
0:16:23.47,000 --> 0:16:26,000
that wants to be free, it's us.

370
0:16:26.575,000 --> 0:16:29,000
Thank you very much.

371
0:16:29.937,000 --> 0:16:31,000
Thank you. (Applause)

372
0:16:32.295,000 --> 0:16:33,000
Hack the planet!

